answers.body_markdown:
You have all the wished data in the PubSub message. Be careful, the format of PubSub message [is slightly different if you use function event format](https://cloud.google.com/functions/docs/calling/pubsub#event_structure). The timestamp and the messageId are in the context object

[Message format](https://cloud.google.com/pubsub/docs/reference/rest/v1/PubsubMessage)
```
   {
     &quot;message&quot;: {
       &quot;attributes&quot;: {
         &quot;key&quot;: &quot;value&quot;
       },
       &quot;data&quot;: &quot;SGVsbG8gQ2xvdWQgUHViL1N1YiEgSGVyZSBpcyBteSBtZXNzYWdlIQ==&quot;,
       &quot;messageId&quot;: &quot;136969346945&quot;,
       &quot;publishTime&quot;: &quot;2014-10-02T15:01:23.045123456Z&quot;
     },
     &quot;subscription&quot;: &quot;projects/myproject/subscriptions/mysubscription&quot;
   }
```

Data are base64 encoded. I recommend you to make a JSON with your data and to publish this json in PubSub. You can get a base64 string but after decoding, you have your JSON and you can use your data.

You also have the `publishedTime`, time of publication in the PubSub. You don&#39;t have the pull time. You can have it by doing a `time = Now()` in your message handler.

Now, you have all your data. You can build a BigQuery row with `&lt;your data&gt;,messageId,publishedTime`. You can build a file (a CSV or JSON line for example) and [perform a load job into bigquery](https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/docs/loading-data), or [use stream write](https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/streaming-data-into-bigquery). All depends on your requirements/preferences.

